title: If the UK participates in European Parliament elections, what percentage of votes will the Change UK Party win?
preds: Out of 73 seats, given that they have 1 seat, it's unlikely they'll hit 4 seats in order to be between 5 and 10%.

They were a spent political force before they even started. Incoherent views, incoherent brand and marketing. Incoherence abounds. Their logo actually repels and alongside their name will probably cause confusion on the ballot paper.
I expect remain votes  to be split between Lib Dem, Labour, Change and SNP.
There is no trust in UKs economical and political situation at the moment.
I don’t think people want anything reasonable and logical right now

Poll average is about 4% and slowly dropping. It's a volatile polling situation with new parties and hard to judge turnout, so there's a decent chance of a polling error. But under 5% is strong favourite. Over 10% is almost unthinkable given a lot of polls showing them not benefiting from the anti-establishment surge which is boosting LD/Green/Brexit Party.
A  YouGov poll of 7,192 voters conducted between May 8-9 projected Change UK would win 5 percent of the vote share at the European elections.

Four days to go. An average of the 7 most recent polls weighted by sample size puts Change UK on 4.1%. Latest polling figures; 3%, 6%, 5%*, 3%, 4%, 4%*, 3% * Large sample size The difference between what the pollsters forecast for each party in 2014 and the actual results; 1.5% UKIP 
1.0% Labour 
2.0% Conservative 
1.5% LibDem 
1.5% Others Crowd: 52%, 36%, 8%, 2%, 2% https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019_European_Parliament_election_in_the_United_Kingdom#Opinion_polls
I believe the British are done with this Brexit nonsense. Additionally Brexit supporters are less likely to vote in an election for a government they want no part of.
They should be in a remain coalition. Their promotional & marketing skills are underwhelming.

Change UK are a disaster. Even the remain-supporting Guardian hates them; https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/may/16/change-uk-is-dying-before-it-even-learned-to-walk As pro-EU voters switch from the Tories and Labour to the LibDems and Green, somehow Change UK who also support remaining in the EU are actually declining in the polls; https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019_European_Parliament_election_in_the_United_Kingdom#Opinion_polls The reason? Things like this "look at your hands" moment; https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XRsYv3A5Hpg

There's infighting in the party and some candidates have stepped down already. It reflected poorly on them when they split from their respective parties, I don't think the damage to the old parties was that drastic.

It might even be higher. The European elections will most likely be used by people to express their views on Brexit, so the change, Lib Dems and Brexit parties will receive a relatively high number of votes. They will lose those votes again in a general election.
I'd have liked the option 'who is change UK party'
The party hasn't galvanized enough of a following among the public
There's no real momentum behind them. Lib Dems and greens have much more support.
I think Liberal Democrat’s will take the greatest share of the remain vote
A lot of pro-Eu vote will go to Labour or Lib Dems, and some to Greens. The whole election is going to be a second referendum, effectively
The two lower bands are extremely unlikely. Polls probably overestimate on-the-day support, so 20 seems right
Literally zero campaigning, no by-elections stood, confusion as to what they're about.
Shifting down because their support has just collapsed in recent polling.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019_European_Parliament_election_in_the_United_Kingdom The average of the 5 polls listed in May is just under 5% though only two are clearly less than 5%.
I am basing this on polls currently pointing at 9-10% and assumed margin of error: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019_European_Parliament_election_in_the_United_Kingdom#Opinion_polls
LibDem / Greens have a similar agenda on a more coherent platform. Tactical voting will count against Change UK.

They rose from 4% in early march to 9% in mid April and seem to have tapered off since then. I wonder if this is a plateau or they have room to grow. Given how well the Lib Dems did in local elections last week, I think these two party's may be going after the same pool of voters which will limit their upside more than their downside.

This protest group of refugees from the main stream parties with a pro EU agenda will not attract a lot of voters.
With little funding and a mix of ideologies beyond Brexit it will  be hard to pull over 5% of the vote in a large turn out and less than 10% if the turn out of voters is moderate to small.

Change UK's poll ratings have been volatile in recent weeks. However, their refusal to co-operate with other Remain parties, the leaking of an aggressively anti-Lib Dem strategy document, and the momentum picked up by the Lib Dems and Greens in the local elections are all likely to hurt Change UK's prospects, most likely putting them in the 5-10% bracket.
Hmm, Red Tories. Tough to tell... There is no baseline or reference point. Just lucky guess.
